ale scholar who has come under fire for describing himself as a feminist critic, he reflects on such issues as identity politics and the politics of academia, affirmative action, and the Million Man March.By connecting his personal experiences with larger political, cultural, and professional questions, Awkward uses his life as a palette on which to blend equations of race and reading, urbanity and mutilation, alcoholism, pain, gender, learning, sex, literature, and love.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 0aAfrican American college teachersvBiography. 0aCriticszUnited StatesvBiography. 0aEnglish teacherszUnited StatesvBiography. 0aFeminism and literaturezUnited States. 0aFeminist literary criticism. 0aMale feministszUnited StatesvBiography. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Cultural Heritage.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Archive eBook-Package 1964-1999z978311071360240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822378372zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822378372423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822378372.jpg  a978-3-11-071360-2  DUK Archive eBook-Package 1964-1999c1964d1999  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles